{ During my games to reach the score of 500 played with Black, I have often come across users playing the Wayward attack opening with the queen. This opening was considered by many experienced users to be unsuitable for a satisfying game because, if well defended, it inevitably leads to a disadvantage for white at the end of the development of the opening. The problem, however, is that when playing with very low level players (eg 0-500) it is easy for those who play with black do not know how to defend themselves and in the end White manages to win by checkmate in a few moves.

Here I report 3 games in which I suffered this attack without knowing how to respond:
https://www.chess.com/game/live/30494370735
https://www.chess.com/game/live/30305952817
https://www.chess.com/game/live/29508579067

The goal of this article is to understand how to defend against this attack.

Wayward's opening includes the following moves: 1. e4, e5; 2. Rh5, ...; thus arriving at a chessboard configuration like the diagraam.

As you can see, the Queen on h5 threatens the pawn on e5 and the weak pawn on f7. Here the player has two defense possibilities. }
