{ Let's see another variation of the Wayward Queen Attack. Let's go back to the moves: e4, e5, Qh5. This time, however, instead of defending the Pawn on e5 with Nc6. } { [%cal Rh5e5,Rh5f7] }
1... Nf6 { Notice how this move does not remove the threats on the e5 and f7 pawns. Let the Queen take the pawn on e5 in such a way, however, that we can continue our development. } { [%cal Rh5e5,Rh5f7] } 2. Qxe5+ { White then moves with Qxe5 + and checks the King. Black defends the check with Be7. } 2... Be7 { As you can see, Black has no compelling threats. At this point any development could continue with Nf3, O-O. } 3. Nf3 { Black replies with O-O. } 3... O-O { The development could follow with Bc4 putting pressure on the f7 Pawn. } 4. Bc4 { Black responds with Re8 so as to increase pressure on the Queen. } 4... Re8 { If White decides to defend himself with O-O castling, Black can continue with Bb4 leaving the Rook unguarded which, however, is defended by the Queen. } 5. O-O { Black continue with Bb4. } 5... Bb4 { If White plays d3. } 6. d3 { Black can respond with d5 square protected by the knight on f6. } 6... d5 { Then Blaack can continue with Nxe4. } { [%cal Rf6e4] } *


